\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Algebraic Topology Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Aaron Bailey
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some of my notes from my reading of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Algebraic Topology
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by Hatcher.
 The primary purpose will be to write down definitions, clarify things in
 need of clarification, and complete the exercises.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part*
Chapter 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter zero discusses the geometric notions of homotopies (a definition
 to be clarified later).
 It can be summarized by stating that two spaces are equivalent if the space
 can be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shrunk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 down to a core lines which are then homeomorphic (e.g.
 B and 8 would both shrink down to homeomorphic curves).
 Hatcher goes on to parameterize such shrinkage and give our first definition.
 A 
\series bold
deformation retraction
\series default
 of a s[ace 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 onto a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a family of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}:X\rightarrow X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in I$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}=\text{id}_{X}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=A$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}|_{A}=\text{id}_{A}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The family 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 should be continuous in the sense that the associated map 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times I\rightarrow X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,t)\mapsto f_{t}(x)$
\end_inset

, is continuous.
 To make intuitive such continuity, we have that for some open set 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}(B)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in I$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 an open disk in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 encapsulating some open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which gets mapped to that subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

